{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614399"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:44:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:44:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16362"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16362"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9053"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114230"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9053"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96230"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7196"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22166"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114230"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old woman presents with a two day history of double vision. A full cranial nerve examination is done and the following is noted when the patient is asked to look to her left (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerves has been affected ?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III)","Trochlear nerve (cranial nerve IV)","Optic nerve (cranial nerve II)","Abducens nerve (cranial nerve VI)","Trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is unable to move her left eye to the left. She has a left lateral rectus muscle palsy. These are physical signs consistent with a left abducens nerve palsy. The lateral rectus muscle is uniquely innervated by the abducens nerve (cranial nerve VI), which has the longest intracranial course of all cranial nerves, making it vulnerable to injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe abducens nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve VI) innervates only the lateral rectus muscle, which abducts the eye (moves it laterally). When this nerve is damaged, the eye turns medially at rest due to unopposed action of the medial rectus, and the patient experiences horizontal diplopia that worsens on attempted lateral gaze to the affected side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe oculomotor nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve III) innervates most other extraocular muscles including the medial rectus, superior rectus, inferior rectus, and inferior oblique muscles, as well as the levator palpebrae superioris.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe trochlear nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve IV) innervates only the superior oblique muscle, which intorts and depresses the eye when it is adducted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe optic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve II) is responsible for vision and does not have any motor function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe trigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve V) provides sensory innervation to the face and motor innervation to the muscles of mastication, but has no role in eye movement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The abducens nerve (cranial nerve VI) innervates only the lateral rectus muscle, which abducts the eye.","Each extraocular muscle is innervated by a specific cranial nerve, which is crucial for coordinated eye movement.","Isolated lateral rectus palsy presents with horizontal diplopia worse on attempted lateral gaze to the affected side."],"references":["Nguyen V, Reddy V, Varacallo M. Neuroanatomy, Cranial Nerve 6 (Abducens). 2022 Nov 21. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613463.","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u2019s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96230"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16362"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21266"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21266"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tgjR7ynhxe7vdpP76T2EJrM9IxAjL4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tgjR7ynhxe7vdpP76T2EJrM9IxAjL4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":399}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96230"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T13:57:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T13:57:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9053"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114230"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount